ğŸ§  Key Learnings
Git allows multiple remotes per repository.

Always verify remotes using git remote -v.

File changes must be staged before commit.

Pushing explicitly requires:

git push <remote> <branch>
Production Git tasks require precision â€” small mistakes can overwrite code.

ğŸ¤ Interview Questions
Q1. What is a Git remote?
A remote is a reference to another Git repository location.

Q2. Why use multiple remotes?
To sync code across different servers or environments.

Q3. Difference between origin and custom remotes?
origin is default; custom remotes allow pushing to additional repos.

Q4. What happens if you push without committing?
Nothing â€” Git only pushes committed changes.

Q5. How do you verify a successful push?
Using:

git log
git remote -v
